{"cursor":"35452","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Positional notation' or 'place-value notation' is a method of representing or\nencoding numbers. Positional notation is distinguished from other notations\n(such as Roman numerals) for its use of the same symbol for the different orders\nof magnitude (for example, the \"ones place\", \"tens place\", \"hundreds place\").\nThis greatly simplified arithmetic and led to the quick spread of the notation\nacross the world.\n\nWith the use of a radix point (decimal point), the notation can be extended to\ninclude fractions and the numeric expansions of real numbers. The HinduâArabic\nnumeral system is an example for a positional notation, based on the number 10.\n","linknr":429,"url":"Positional_number_system","recorded":1362372651,"links":45,"instances":["mathematics","punctuation","number","sumer","mathematics","number","mathematics"],"pdf":["http://sciences.aum.edu/~sbrown/Hindu%20Arabic%20and%20Chinese.pdf"],"categories":["Positional numeral systems","Mathematical notation","Articles containing proofs"],"headings":["History","Mathematics","Applications","Non-standard positional numeral systems","Non-positional positions","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/7/4/374351c4a4dbb61e3c2fe2d3a74e5688.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/7/3/0738a0c4f9aa503a9d27ba1d2b4d7514.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/7/1/371089e4731fd6118c2b66d79ab677fb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/e/c/aecc36135eb30b8a37173262fffdb261.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/1/f/f1f5fbbdbd9af47154344e258894b18f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/0/5/2054060eb221439106d1a5ff575e79a1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/c/4/dc4da840e230a04febabcbf2778bb0bc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/b/6/3b611b0b88b1bf9372af59a4338fb484.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/6/c/86c3d020de